      "stimulus_html": "",
      "stem_html": "<p>The first step in the biological degradation of lysine is reductive amination with <i>α</i>-ketoglutarate to give saccharopine. Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate (NADPH), a relative of NADH, is the reducing agent. Show the mechanism.</p>\n<img class=\"scaled-down\" src=\"https://exercises.openstax.org/rails/active_storage/blobs/proxy/eyJfcmFpbHMiOnsibWVzc2FnZSI6IkJBaHBBcjRaIiwiZXhwIjpudWxsLCJwdXIiOiJibG9iX2lkIn19--dedae959ce3890e71d025ccf36de6af967bfe7e9/OChem_26_EC_022.jpg\" alt=\"L-Lysine reacts with alpha-ketoglutarate and nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate hydrogen to form saccharopine and nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide phosphate cation.\">",
